SIMPLE: revest
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Revest
<hw>Re*vest"</hw> <pr>(r⟦emac⟧*v⟦ecr⟧st")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<ety>[OF <ets>reverstir</ets>, F. <ets>rev⟦ecir⟧tir</ets>, L.
<ets>revestire</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>vestire</ets> to
clothe, fr. <ets>vestis</ets> a garment. See <er>Vestry</er>, and cf.
<er>Revet</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To clothe again; to cover, as
with a robe; to robe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her, nathless, . . . the enchanter⟦br⟧
Did thus <qex>revest</qex> and decked with due habiliments.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To vest again with possession or office; <as>as, to
<ex>revest</ex> a magistrate with authority</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Revest
<hw>Re*vest"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take effect or vest again,
as a title; to revert to former owner; <as>as, the title or right
<ex>revests</ex> in A after alienation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revestiary</ent>⟦br⟧
